<doc id="25977" wikidata="Q44649" url="?curid=25977" title="Ideal (ring theory)">
<text>In mathematics, and more specifically in ring theory, an ideal of a ring is a special subset of its elements. Ideals generalize certain subsets of the integers, such as the even numbers or the multiples of 3. Addition and subtraction of even numbers preserves evenness, and multiplying an even number by any integer (even or odd) results in an even number; these closure and absorption properties are the defining properties of an ideal. An ideal can be used to construct a quotient ring in a way similar to how, in group theory, a normal subgroup can be used to construct a quotient group.

Among the integers, the ideals correspond one-for-one with the non-negative integers: in this ring, every ideal is a principal ideal consisting of the multiples of a single non-negative number. However, in other rings, the ideals may not correspond directly to the ring elements, and certain properties of integers, when generalized to rings, attach more naturally to the ideals than to the elements of the ring. For instance, the prime ideals of a ring are analogous to prime numbers, and the Chinese remainder theorem can be generalized to ideals. There is a version of unique prime factorization for the ideals of a Dedekind domain (a type of ring important in number theory).

The related, but distinct, concept of an ideal in order theory is derived from the notion of ideal in ring theory. A fractional ideal is a generalization of an ideal, and the usual ideals are sometimes called integral ideals for clarity.

== History ==
Ernst Kummer invented the concept of ideal numbers to serve as the &quot;missing&quot; factors in number rings in which unique factorization fails; here the word &quot;ideal&quot; is in the sense of existing in imagination only, in analogy with &quot;ideal&quot; objects in geometry such as points at infinity.
In 1876, Richard Dedekind replaced Kummer&#x27;s undefined concept by concrete sets of numbers, sets that he called ideals, in the third edition of Dirichlet&#x27;s book &quot;Vorlesungen über Zahlentheorie&quot;, to which Dedekind had added many supplements.
Later the notion was extended beyond number rings to the setting of polynomial rings and other commutative rings by David Hilbert and especially Emmy Noether.

== Definitions ==
Given a ring , a left ideal is a subset of that is a subgroup of the additive group of formula_1 that &quot;absorbs multiplication from the left by elements of &quot;; that is, formula_2 is a left ideal if it satisfies the following two conditions:
# formula_3 is a subgroup of ,
# For every formula_4 and every , the product formula_5 is in .

In other words, a left ideal is a left submodule of , considered as a left module over itself.

A right ideal is defined similarly, with the condition formula_6 replaced by . A two-sided ideal is a left ideal that is also a right ideal.

If the ring is commutative, the three definitions are the same, and one talks simply of an ideal. In the non-commutative case, &quot;ideal&quot; is often used instead of &quot;two-sided ideal&quot;.

If is a left, right or two-sided ideal, the relation formula_7 if and only if
:formula_8
is an equivalence relation on , and the set of equivalence classes forms a left, right or bi module denoted formula_9 and called the &quot;quotient&quot; of by . (It is an instance of a congruence relation and is a generalization of modular arithmetic.)

If the ideal is two-sided, formula_9 is a ring, and the function 
:formula_11 
that associates to each element of its equivalence class is a surjective ring homomorphism that has the ideal as its kernel. Conversely, the kernel of a ring homomorphism is a two-sided ideal. Therefore, &quot;the two-sided ideals are exactly the kernels of ring homomorphisms.&quot;

=== Note on convention ===
By convention, a ring has the multiplicative identity. But some authors do not require a ring to have the multiplicative identity; i.e., for them, a ring is a rng. For a rng , a left ideal is a subrng with the additional property that formula_12 is in for every formula_4 and every formula_14. (Right and two-sided ideals are defined similarly.) For a ring, an ideal (say a left ideal) is rarely a subring; since a subring shares the same multiplicative identity with the ambient ring , if were a subring, for every formula_4, we have formula_16 i.e., formula_17.

The notion of an ideal does not involve associativity; thus, an ideal is also defined for non-associative rings (often without the multiplicative identity) such as a Lie algebra.

== Examples and properties ==
(For the sake of brevity, some results are stated only for left ideals but are usually also true for right ideals with appropriate notation changes.)
* In a ring &quot;R&quot;, the set &quot;R&quot; itself forms a two-sided ideal of &quot;R&quot; called the unit ideal. It is often also denoted by formula_18 since it is precisely the two-sided ideal generated (see below) by the unity . Also, the set formula_19 consisting of only the additive identity 0&quot;R&quot; forms a two-sided ideal called the zero ideal and is denoted by . Every (left, right or two-sided) ideal contains the zero ideal and is contained in the unit ideal.
* An (left, right or two-sided) ideal that is not the unit ideal is called a proper ideal (as it is a proper subset). Note: a left ideal formula_20 is proper if and only if it does not contain a unit element, since if formula_21 is a unit element, then formula_22 for every . Typically there are plenty of proper ideals. In fact, if &quot;R&quot; is a skew-field, then formula_23 are its only ideals and conversely: that is, a nonzero ring &quot;R&quot; is a skew-field if formula_23 are the only left (or right) ideals. (Proof: if formula_25 is a nonzero element, then the principal left ideal formula_26 (see below) is nonzero and thus formula_27; i.e., formula_28 for some nonzero . Likewise, formula_29 for some nonzero formula_30. Then formula_31.)
* The even integers form an ideal in the ring formula_32 of all integers, since the sum of any two even integers is even, and the product of any integer with an even integer is also even; this ideal is usually denoted by . More generally, the set of all integers divisible by a fixed integer formula_33 is an ideal denoted . In fact, every non-zero ideal of the ring formula_32 is generated by its smallest positive element, as a consequence of Euclidean division, so formula_32 is a principal ideal domain.
* The set of all polynomials with real coefficients that are divisible by the polynomial formula_36 is an ideal in the ring of all real-coefficient polynomials .
* Take a ring formula_1 and positive integer . For each , the set of all formula_38 matrices with entries in formula_1 whose formula_40-th row is zero is a right ideal in the ring formula_41 of all formula_38 matrices with entries in . It is not a left ideal. Similarly, for each , the set of all formula_38 matrices whose formula_44-th &quot;column&quot; is zero is a left ideal but not a right ideal.
* The ring formula_45 of all continuous functions formula_46 from formula_47 to formula_47 under pointwise multiplication contains the ideal of all continuous functions formula_46 such that . Another ideal in formula_45 is given by those functions that vanish for large enough arguments, i.e. those continuous functions formula_46 for which there exists a number formula_52 such that formula_53 whenever .
* A ring is called a simple ring if it is nonzero and has no two-sided ideals other than . Thus, a skew-field is simple and a simple commutative ring is a field. The matrix ring over a skew-field is a simple ring.
* If formula_54 is a ring homomorphism, then the kernel formula_55 is a two-sided ideal of . By definition, , and thus if formula_56 is not the zero ring (so ), then formula_57 is a proper ideal. More generally, for each left ideal &quot;I&quot; of &quot;S&quot;, the pre-image formula_58 is a left ideal. If &quot;I&quot; is a left ideal of &quot;R&quot;, then formula_59 is a left ideal of the subring formula_60 of &quot;S&quot;: unless &quot;f&quot; is surjective, formula_59 need not be an ideal of &quot;S&quot;; see also #Extension and contraction of an ideal below.
* Ideal correspondence: Given a surjective ring homomorphism , there is a bijective order-preserving correspondence between the left (resp. right, two-sided) ideals of formula_1 containing the kernel of formula_46 and the left (resp. right, two-sided) ideals of formula_56: the correspondence is given by formula_65 and the pre-image . Moreover, for commutative rings, this bijective correspondence restricts to prime ideals, maximal ideals, and radical ideals (see the Types of ideals section for the definitions of these ideals).
* (For those who know modules) If &quot;M&quot; is a left &quot;R&quot;-module and formula_66 a subset, then the annihilator formula_67 of &quot;S&quot; is a left ideal. Given ideals formula_68 of a commutative ring &quot;R&quot;, the &quot;R&quot;-annihilator of formula_69 is an ideal of &quot;R&quot; called the ideal quotient of formula_20 by formula_71 and is denoted by ; it is an instance of idealizer in commutative algebra.
* Let formula_72 be an ascending chain of left ideals in a ring &quot;R&quot;; i.e., formula_56 is a totally ordered set and formula_74 for each . Then the union formula_75 is a left ideal of &quot;R&quot;. (Note: this fact remains true even if &quot;R&quot; is without the unity 1.)
* The above fact together with Zorn&#x27;s lemma proves the following: if formula_76 is a possibly empty subset and formula_77 is a left ideal that is disjoint from &quot;E&quot;, then there is an ideal that is maximal among the ideals containing formula_78 and disjoint from &quot;E&quot;. (Again this is still valid if the ring &quot;R&quot; lacks the unity 1.) When formula_79, taking formula_80 and , in particular, there exists a left ideal that is maximal among proper left ideals (often simply called a maximal left ideal); see Krull&#x27;s theorem for more. 
*An arbitrary union of ideals need not be an ideal, but the following is still true: given a possibly empty subset &quot;X&quot; of &quot;R&quot;, there is the smallest left ideal containing &quot;X&quot;, called the left ideal generated by &quot;X&quot; and is denoted by . Such an ideal exists since it is the intersection of all left ideals containing &quot;X&quot;. Equivalently, formula_81 is the set of all the (finite) left &quot;R&quot;-linear combinations of elements of &quot;X&quot; over &quot;R&quot;:
