* formula_20 is generated by elements that form a regular sequence modulo .
(More generally, the difference between a product and an intersection of ideals is measured by the Tor functor: .)

An integral domain is called a Dedekind domain if for each pair of ideals formula_132, there is an ideal formula_127 such that . It can then be shown that every nonzero ideal of a Dedekind domain can be uniquely written as a product of maximal ideals, a generalization of the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.

