Remark: Let &quot;K&quot; be a field extension of &quot;L&quot;, and let &quot;B&quot; and &quot;A&quot; be the rings of integers of &quot;K&quot; and &quot;L&quot;, respectively. Then &quot;B&quot; is an integral extension of &quot;A&quot;, and we let &quot;f&quot; be the inclusion map from &quot;A&quot; to &quot;B&quot;. The behaviour of a prime ideal formula_195 of &quot;A&quot; under extension is one of the central problems of algebraic number theory.

The following is sometimes useful: a prime ideal formula_196 is a contraction of a prime ideal if and only if . (Proof: Assuming the latter, note formula_197 intersects , a contradiction. Now, the prime ideals of formula_198 correspond to those in &quot;B&quot; that are disjoint from . Hence, there is a prime ideal formula_199 of &quot;B&quot;, disjoint from , such that formula_200 is a maximal ideal containing . One then checks that formula_199 lies over . The converse is obvious.)

== Generalizations ==
Ideals can be generalized to any monoid object , where formula_1 is the object where the monoid structure has been forgotten. A left ideal of formula_1 is a subobject formula_2 that &quot;absorbs multiplication from the left by elements of &quot;; that is, formula_2 is a left ideal if it satisfies the following two conditions:
# formula_2 is a subobject of formula_1
# For every formula_208 and every , the product formula_209 is in .

A right ideal is defined with the condition &quot;&quot; replaced by &quot;&#x27;&quot;. A two-sided ideal is a left ideal that is also a right ideal, and is sometimes simply called an ideal. When formula_1 is a commutative monoid object respectively, the definitions of left, right, and two-sided ideal coincide, and the term ideal is used alone.

An ideal can also be thought of as a specific type of -module. If we consider formula_1 as a left formula_1-module (by left multiplication), then a left ideal formula_2 is really just a left sub-module of . In other words, formula_2 is a left (right) ideal of formula_1 if and only if it is a left (right) formula_1-module that is a subset of . formula_2 is a two-sided ideal if it is a sub-formula_1-bimodule of .

Example: If we let , an ideal of formula_32 is an abelian group that is a subset of , i.e. formula_220 for some . So these give all the ideals of .

